<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,152,738]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,313,591,617]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Remarks.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sowerby II" authorityYear="1858" box="[490,736,592,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="madagascariensis">
<emphasis box="[490,736,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">C. madagascariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often difficult to distinguish from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Born" authorityYear="1778" box="[1194,1353,592,617]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pennaceus">
<emphasis box="[1194,1353,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">C. pennaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the consistently straight-sided apex and rather uniformly reticulate pattern on the body whorl of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sowerby II" authorityYear="1858" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="madagascariensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">C. madagascariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distinguishes the latter. Although previously reported only from Tuticorin, during the three years of this survey not even a single specimen was encountered at Tuticorin.
</paragraph>
